# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: buck-weaver
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:buck-weaver/1912-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1912 throughout the world.
[src:buck-weaver/1917-chicago-white-sox-season] The **1917 Chicago White Sox** dominated the American League with a record of 100–54.
[src:buck-weaver/1917-chicago-white-sox-season] The 100 wins is a club record that still stands.
[src:buck-weaver/1917-chicago-white-sox-season] Their offense was first in runs scored while their pitching staff led the league with a 2.16 ERA.
[src:buck-weaver/1917-chicago-white-sox-season] Facing the New York Giants in the 1917 World Series, the team clinched the series in six games, thanks in large part to the workhorse efforts of Eddie Cicotte and Red Faber.
[src:buck-weaver/1917-chicago-white-sox-season] It would be the team's last world championship until 2005.
[src:buck-weaver/1917-chicago-white-sox-season] There were accusations of this series not being completely "on the level," especially after the Black Sox Scandal of 1919.
[src:buck-weaver/1917-chicago-white-sox-season] The most notable play involved Heinie Zimmerman of the Giants chasing Eddie Collins across home plate in the deciding game.
[src:buck-weaver/1917-chicago-white-sox-season] Zimmerman was later banned from organized baseball for throwing games.
[src:buck-weaver/1917-world-series] The **1917** **World Series** was the championship series of Major League Baseball's (MLB) 1917 season.
[src:buck-weaver/1917-world-series] The 14th edition of the World Series, it was a best-of-seven playoff between the American League (AL) champion Chicago White Sox and the National League (NL) champion New York Giants.
[src:buck-weaver/1917-world-series] The White Sox won the series in six games.
[src:buck-weaver/1917-world-series] The series was played against the backdrop of World War I, which dominated American newspapers both that year and the next.
[src:buck-weaver/1917-world-series] The strong Chicago White Sox club finished the 1917 season with a 100–54 record, which remains their only 100-win season in franchise history to date.
[src:buck-weaver/1917-world-series] Their next World Series-winning team in 2005 finished the regular season with a 99–63 record.
[src:buck-weaver/1917-world-series] The Sox won Game 1 of the Series in Chicago 2–1 behind a complete game by Eddie Cicotte.
[src:buck-weaver/1917-world-series] Happy Felsch hit a home run in the fourth inning that provided the winning margin.
[src:buck-weaver/1917-world-series] In Game 2 the Sox beat the Giants 7–2 behind another complete game effort by Red Faber to take a 2–0 lead in the Series.
[src:buck-weaver/1917-world-series] Back in New York for Game 3, Cicotte again threw a complete game, but the Sox could not muster a single run against Giants' starter Rube Benton and lost 2–0.
[src:buck-weaver/1917-world-series] In Game 4 the Sox were shut out again 5–0 by Ferdie Schupp.
[src:buck-weaver/1917-world-series] Faber threw another complete game, but the Series was even at 2–2 going back to Chicago.
[src:buck-weaver/1917-world-series] Reb Russell started Game 5 in Chicago, but only faced three batters before giving way to Cicotte.
[src:buck-weaver/1917-world-series] Going into the bottom of the seventh inning, Chicago was down 5–2, but they rallied to score three in the seventh and three in the eighth to win 8–5.
[src:buck-weaver/1917-world-series] Faber pitched the final two innings for the win.
[src:buck-weaver/1917-world-series] In Game 6 the Sox took an early 3–0 lead and on the strength of another complete-game victory from Faber (his third of the Series) won 4–2 and clinched the World Championship.
[src:buck-weaver/1917-world-series] Eddie Collins was the hitting hero, batting .409 over the six-game series while Cicotte and Faber combined to pitch 50 out of a total 52 World Series innings to lead the staff.
[src:buck-weaver/1917-world-series] The decisive game underscored the Giants' post-season frustrations, featuring a famous rundown in which Giants' third baseman Heinie Zimmerman futilely chased the speedy Eddie Collins toward home plate with what would be the Series-winning run.
[src:buck-weaver/1917-world-series] Catcher Bill Rariden had run up the third base line to start a rundown, expecting pitcher Rube Benton or first baseman Walter Holke to cover the plate.
[src:buck-weaver/1917-world-series] However, neither of them budged, forcing Zimmerman to chase Collins while pawing helplessly in the air with the ball in an attempt to tag him.
[src:buck-weaver/1917-world-series] Two years before the issue of baseball betting reached its peak, Zimmerman found himself having to publicly deny purposely allowing the run to score, i.e. to deny that he had "thrown" the game.
[src:buck-weaver/1917-world-series] In truth, McGraw blamed Benton and Holke for failing to cover the plate.
[src:buck-weaver/1917-world-series] Zimmerman would eventually be banned for life due to various accusations of corruption.
[src:buck-weaver/1917-world-series] The White Sox, who were essentially dismantled following the 1920 season by baseball commissioner Kenesaw Mountain Landis due to the Black Sox Scandal in the 1919 World Series, did not make it to another World Series until 1959, and did not win another World Series until 2005.
[src:buck-weaver/1917-world-series] This was the first of nine meetings between teams from Chicago and New York City for a major professional sports championship.
[src:buck-weaver/1917-world-series] Fred McMullin drove in Chicago's first run, and Happy Felsch's homer made it 2–0.
[src:buck-weaver/1917-world-series] Giants pitcher Slim Sallee knocked in his side's only run with a single after a Lew McCarty triple.
[src:buck-weaver/1917-world-series] Shoeless Joe Jackson's two-run single capped a five-run fourth inning for the White Sox, who knocked out Giants starter Ferdie Schupp in the second inning.
[src:buck-weaver/1917-world-series] The home team won for the third straight time as the series moved to New York.
[src:buck-weaver/1917-world-series] The only runs of a snappy 1 hour, 55 minute game came on a Dave Robertson triple, Walter Holke double and a single by George Burns.
[src:buck-weaver/1917-world-series] The first of a pair of homers by Giants center fielder Benny Kauff was an inside-the-park one that sailed over Sox center fielder Happy Felsch's head.
[src:buck-weaver/1917-world-series] The other came in the eighth off Chicago reliever Dave Danforth.
[src:buck-weaver/1917-world-series] Even though Red Faber would start Games 4 and 6, he was brought in from the bullpen to close Game 5.
[src:buck-weaver/1917-world-series] Taking no chances, the Sox yanked starter Reb Russell after just three batters, all of whom reached base.
[src:buck-weaver/1917-world-series] A three-error third inning behind Eddie Cicotte put the Giants up 4–1.
[src:buck-weaver/1917-world-series] But after a game-tying rally in the seventh, the Sox won it in the eighth as Happy Felsch greeted reliever Pol Perritt with an RBI single.
[src:buck-weaver/1917-world-series] It was the fifth straight win by the home team in this Series.
[src:buck-weaver/1917-world-series] A pair of errors proved costly to the Giants in a three-run fourth when Chick Gandil and Ray Schalk followed with RBI hits.
[src:buck-weaver/1917-world-series] New York's hopes rose with a Buck Herzog triple in the next inning that made it 3–2.
[src:buck-weaver/1917-world-series] But with the workhorse Faber holding the Giants at bay the rest of the way, the Sox got an insurance run in the ninth on hits by Buck Weaver and Nemo Leibold, and the Series was theirs.
[src:buck-weaver/1917-world-series] It would be their last championship until 2005.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-chicago-white-sox-season] The **1919 Chicago White Sox season** was their 19th season in the American League.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-chicago-white-sox-season] They won 88 games to advance to the World Series but lost to the Cincinnati Reds.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-chicago-white-sox-season] More significantly, some of the players were found to have taken money from gamblers in return for throwing the series.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-chicago-white-sox-season] The "Black Sox Scandal" had permanent ramifications for baseball, including the establishment of the office of Commissioner of Baseball.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-chicago-white-sox-season] In 1919, Eddie Cicotte led the majors with 29 wins and 30 complete games, going 29–7 for the season with a 1.82 ERA (2nd in AL) and 110 strikeouts (7th in AL).
[src:buck-weaver/1919-chicago-white-sox-season] He also led the AL in innings pitched with 240 (shared with Washington Senators pitcher Jim Shaw).
[src:buck-weaver/1919-chicago-white-sox-season] Right fielder Joe Jackson hit .351 (4th in AL) with 7 home runs, 96 RBIs (3rd in AL) and had 181 hits (3rd in AL, only 10 fewer than league leader Ty Cobb of the Detroit Tigers).
[src:buck-weaver/1919-chicago-white-sox-season] Shoeless Joe headed an offense that scored the most runs of any team.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-chicago-white-sox-season] The **Black Sox Scandal** refers to a number of events that took place around and during the play of the 1919 World Series.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-chicago-white-sox-season] The name "Black Sox" also refers to the Chicago White Sox team from that era.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-chicago-white-sox-season] Eight members of the Chicago franchise were banned from baseball for throwing (intentionally losing) games.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-chicago-white-sox-season] The conspiracy was the brainchild of White Sox first baseman Arnold "Chick" Gandil and Joseph "Sport" Sullivan, who was a professional gambler of Gandil's acquaintance.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-chicago-white-sox-season] New York gangster Arnold Rothstein supplied the major connections needed.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-chicago-white-sox-season] The money was supplied by Abe Attell, former featherweight boxing champion, who accepted the offer even though he didn't have the $80,000 that the White Sox wanted.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-chicago-white-sox-season] Gandil enlisted seven of his teammates, motivated by a mixture of greed and a dislike of penurious club owner Charles Comiskey, to implement the fix.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-chicago-white-sox-season] Starting pitchers Eddie Cicotte and Claude "Lefty" Williams, outfielders "Shoeless" Joe Jackson and Oscar "Happy" Felsch, and infielder Charles "Swede" Risberg were all involved.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-chicago-white-sox-season] Buck Weaver was also asked to participate, but refused; he was later banned with the others for knowing of the fix but not reporting it.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-chicago-white-sox-season] Utility infielder Fred McMullin was not initially approached but got word of the fix and threatened to report the others unless he was in on the payoff.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-chicago-white-sox-season] Sullivan and his two associates, Sleepy Bill Burns and Billy Maharg, somewhat out of their depth, approached Rothstein to provide the money for the players, who were promised a total of $100,000.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-chicago-white-sox-season] Stories of the "Black Sox" scandal have usually included Comiskey in its gallery of subsidiary villains, focusing in particular on his intentions regarding a clause in Cicotte's contract that would have paid Cicotte an additional $10,000 bonus for winning 30 games.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-chicago-white-sox-season] According to Eliot Asinof's account of the events, *Eight Men Out*, Cicotte was "rested" for the season's final two weeks after reaching his 29th win, presumably to deny him the bonus.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-chicago-white-sox-season] In reality, however, Cicotte started the White Sox's last game of the season, September 28th against the Tigers.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-chicago-white-sox-season] But, with a 1-0 Chicago lead, Chicago manager Kid Gleason took Cicotte out of the game following the second inning, which assured Cicotte could not get his 30th win.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] The **1919 Cincinnati Reds season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds won the National League pennant, then went on to win the 1919 World Series.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] The team's accomplishments were overshadowed by the subsequent Black Sox Scandal, when it was discovered that their American League opponents, the Chicago White Sox had conspired to throw the series.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Reds manager Christy Mathewson, who left the club late in the 1918 season to enlist in the United States Army for World War I, was accidentally gassed during a chemical training exercise and subsequently developed tuberculosis.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Mathewson served with the American Expeditionary Force until February 1919 and was discharged later that month, however, it became apparent that he was too sick to manage the Reds.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Cincinnati replaced Mathewson with Pat Moran.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Moran had previously managed the Philadelphia Phillies from 1915 until 1918, leading the team to a 323–257 record, and won the National League pennant in 1915.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] In the 1915 World Series, the Phillies lost to the Boston Red Sox.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] On February 1, the Reds traded away outfielder Tommy Griffith to the Brooklyn Robins in exchange for first baseman Jake Daubert.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Daubert, who had spent his entire nine-year career with Brooklyn, hit .308 with two home runs, 47 RBI and a league high 15 triples in 108 games during the 1918 season.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Daubert was named the National League Most Valuable Player during the 1913 season, when he led the league with a .350 batting average, two home runs, 52 RBI in 139 games.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] With Daubert now playing first base, the Reds traded away first baseman Hal Chase to the New York Giants for first baseman Walter Holke and catcher Bill Rariden.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Holke was then shipped to the Boston Braves for infielder/outfielder Jimmy Smith.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Rariden batted .224 with 17 RBI in 69 games with the Giants during the 1918 season, while Smith hit .225 with a home run and 14 RBI in 34 games with the Braves.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] In March, the Reds selected pitchers Ray Fisher from the New York Yankees and Slim Sallee from the New York Giants on waivers.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Fisher, who spent the 1918 enlisted in the United States Army, had pitched with New York from 1910 to 1917, earning a 76–78 record with a 2.91 ERA in 219 games pitched.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] His best season was in 1915, as Fisher had a record of 18–11 with a 2.11 ERA in 30 games.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Sallee, who broke into the league with the St.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Louis Cardinals in 1908, had an 8–8 record and a 2.25 ERA in 18 games with the Giants in 1918.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds, who were looking to build off of a solid 68–60 record during the 1918 season, their highest winning percentage since 1904, started off the 1919 season with seven consecutive wins, and nine wins in their first 10 games, to take an early lead in the National League standings.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds did slump over their next 26 games, going 11–15 to drop their overall record to 20–16, and slipped into second place, four games behind the New York Giants.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Cincinnati put together a record of 24–7 in their next 31 games, moving to a 44–23 record and into first place in the National League, just ahead of the Giants.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] By the end of July, despite a very strong 59–28 record, the Reds and Giants were tied for first place.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] On August 3, 1919, up 2.5 games on the second place Giants, 43,000 fans crowded into Redlands Field to see the Reds host the Giants.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] In August, the Reds begin to pull away from the Giants, as on August 26, Cincinnati had a record of 81-34 and had built a nine-game lead over New York.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Also in August, there were accusations that the teams playing the Reds were throwing their games to allow the Reds to win.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds continued to win in the last month of the season, and on September 18, Cincinnati defeated the Brooklyn Robins 2–0 to win their 93rd game of the season, which set a team record, besting the 92 wins the club had in 1898.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Overall, Cincinnati finished the season with a 96–44 record, cruising to the National League pennant, as the team finished in first place for the first time since 1882.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds qualified for the 1919 World Series, as they would face the American League champions, the Chicago White Sox.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Outfielder Edd Roush led the National League with a .321 batting average, and he added four home runs, a team high 71 RBI and 20 stolen bases in 133 games.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Third baseman Heinie Groh batted .310 with a team high five home runs, 63 RBI and 21 stolen bases in 122 games.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Newly acquired first baseman Jake Daubert hit .276 with two home runs and 44 RBI.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Outfielder Greasy Neale led the Reds with 28 stolen bases, while batting .242 with a home run and 54 RBI in 139 games.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Pitcher Hod Eller anchored the pitching staff, as he recorded a 19–9 record with a 2.39 ERA, leading the club with 248.1 innings pitched and 137 strikeouts in 38 games.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Dutch Ruether led the National League in winning percentage, as he finished the season with a 19–6 record and a team best 1.82 ERA in 33 games.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Slim Sallee, who the Reds picked up off of waivers from the New York Giants before the season began, led the club in victories, as he finished the season with a 21–7 record and a 2.06 ERA and had a team high 22 complete games in 29 games.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Ray Fisher, another Reds waiver pickup prior to the season, had a solid 14–5 record with a 2.17 ERA in 26 games.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] With the successful season on the field, the Reds set a club record for attendance, as they drew 532,501 fans to their home games, breaking the team record of 424,643 set in the 1909 season.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds opened the 1919 World Series at home in front of 30,511 fans at Redland Field, the first World Series game in club history.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Dutch Ruether got the start for the Reds, against Eddie Cicotte of the Chicago White Sox.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] After a scoreless top half of the first inning, the Reds Morrie Rath led off the bottom of the inning and was hit by a pitch.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Jake Daubert then hit a single, moving Rath to third base, and Heinie Groh then hit a sacrifice fly, bring Rath home and giving Cincinnati a 1–0 lead.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] The White Sox tied the game in the top of the second inning as a Chick Gandil single scored Shoeless Joe Jackson.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds retook the lead in the bottom of the fourth inning, when Ivey Wingo singled to right field, scoring Larry Kopf.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] With two men on base, pitcher Dutch Ruether helped his own cause, hitting a triple, scoring Greasy Neale and Wingo, opening up the Reds lead to 4–1.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Morrie Rath then doubled to center field, scoring Ruether, increasing the Cincinnati lead to 5–1, followed by a Jake Daubert single, scoring Rath, giving Cincinnati a 6-1 and knocking Eddie Cicotte out of the game.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] With Roy Wilkinson in the ballgame, the Reds added two more runs in the seventh inning, as Heinie Groh singled home Jake Daubert, and Pat Duncan drove in Groh on a groundout, giving Cincinnati an 8–1 lead.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] In the eighth inning, the Reds took a 9–1 lead as Dutch Ruether hit his second triple of the game off of Grover Lowdermilk, driving home Greasy Neale.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Dutch Ruether finished the complete game with a perfect ninth inning, as the Reds took an early 1–0 series lead.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] The second game of the series was played in front of 29,698 fans at Redland Field, with Slim Sallee getting the start for the Reds, against Lefty Williams of the Chicago White Sox.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] After three scoreless innings to start the game, the Reds opened the scoring in the bottom of the fourth inning, as Morrie Rath led off the inning with a walk.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Jake Daubert moved Rath to second base with a sacrifice bunt.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Heinie Groh then walked, followed by a single by Edd Roush, which drove home Rath, giving the Reds a 1–0 lead.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Roush was caught stealing second, making it two outs, however, Pat Duncan walked, the third Reds player to walk in the inning.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Larry Kopf then tripled to center field, scoring Groh and Duncan, giving the Reds a 3–0 lead.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] In the sixth inning, the Reds extended their lead to 4-0 after Edd Roush led off the inning with a walk, and came around to score after a single by Greasy Neale.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] The White Sox cut into the Reds lead in the seventh inning, as Ray Schalk singled home Swede Risberg.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Schalk scored on the play after two throwing errors by the Reds, as the White Sox cut the Reds lead in half to 4–2.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Slim Sallee finished the game with a scoreless ninth inning, getting the complete game, as Cincinnati held on for a 4–2 win, and took a 2–0 series lead.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] The series shifted over to Comiskey Park in Chicago for the third game.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Ray Fisher got the start for Cincinnati, against Dickey Kerr for the White Sox in front of 29,126 fans.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] The White Sox opened the scoring in the second inning, as Chick Gandil singled to left field, scoring Shoeless Joe Jackson and Happy Felsch, giving Chicago a 2–0 lead.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] The Sox added to their lead in the fourth, when Ray Schalk bunted a single, scoring Swede Risberg, as the White Sox took a 3–0 lead.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Dickey Kerr pitched a masterpiece for the White Sox, as he finished with a three hit shutout, as Chicago won the game 3–0, cutting the series lead to 2–1.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] The fourth game of the series was played at Comiskey Park in Chicago, with Jimmy Ring starting for the Reds, against Eddie Cicotte of the White Sox in front of 34,363 fans.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] After four scoreless innings, the Reds caught a break when Pat Duncan reached second base on a throwing error by Eddie Cicotte.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Larry Kopf singled home Duncan, giving Cincinnati a 1–0 lead.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Greasy Neale followed that up with a double to left field, scoring Kopf, and giving the Reds a 2–0 lead.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Jimmy Ring pitched a complete-game shutout for the Reds, holding the White Sox to only three hits, as the Reds took the fourth game by a 2–0 score, and took a 3–1 series lead.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] The fifth game of the series was played at Comiskey Park in Chicago in front of 34,379 fans, as Hod Eller started for the Reds, against Lefty Williams of the White Sox.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] The game was originally scheduled for October 5, however, it was postponed due to rain.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Both Eller and Williams pitched excellent to start the game, as it wasn't until the sixth inning before the Reds opened the scoring.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Hod Eller led off the inning with a double, and came around to scoring after a Morrie Rath single, making it 1-0 for the Reds.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Jake Daubert sacrificed bunted, moving Rath to third base, followed by a walk by Heinie Groh.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Edd Roush then hit a triple to deep center field, scoring Rath and Groh, making it 3-0 for the Reds.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Pat Duncan then hit a sacrifice fly, scoring Roush, extending the Reds lead to 4–0.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] In the ninth, the Reds added another run, as Greasy Neale drove home Pat Duncan when he grounded out.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Hod Eller completed the shutout in the bottom of the inning, as he allowed only three hits in the game, and struck out nine, which included a World Series record six batters in a row, to earn the victory for the Reds, as they took a 4–1 series lead.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] The series moved back to Redland Field in Cincinnati for game six, with Dutch Ruether starting for the Reds, against Dickey Kerr of the White Sox, in front of 32,006 fans.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds took the lead in the second inning, as Jake Daubert singled to right field, and then stole second base.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Edd Roush was then hit by a pitch, and both Daubert and Roush were brought home after a Pat Duncan double, giving the Reds a 2–0 lead.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Cincinnati struck again in the third inning, as Greasy Neale led the inning off with a triple, then came in to score after Dutch Ruether doubled, giving Cincinnati a 3–0 lead.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Morrie Rath drove in Ruether after an error by White Sox shortstop Swede Risberg, as the Reds took a 4–0 lead.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] The White Sox struck back with a run of their own in the fifth inning, as Eddie Collins hit a sacrifice fly, scoring Swede Risberg, cutting the Reds lead to 4–1.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] In the sixth inning, the White Sox cut the lead to 4-2 when Shoeless Joe Jackson singled home Buck Weaver.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Happy Felsch then doubled, scoring Jackson, and cut the Reds lead to 4–3, as Ruether was pulled out of the game, replaced with Jimmy Ring.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Ring allowed a single by Ray Schalk, as Felsch scored, tying the game up at 4-4.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] The game remained tied after nine innings, and in the tenth inning, the White Sox took a 5–4 lead after singled, scoring Buck Weaver.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] In the bottom half of the inning, Kerr finished the complete game victory, as Chicago completed the comeback, winning the game 5-4 and cutting the Reds series lead to 4–2.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] The seventh game of the series was played at Redland Field in front of 13,323 fans, as the Reds started Slim Sallee, against Eddie Cicotte of the White Sox.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Chicago opened the scoring in the top of the first inning, when Shoeless Joe Jackson singled home Eddie Collins, giving Chicago a 1–0 lead.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] In the third inning, Chicago struck again, on another single by Jackson, which scored Collins, as Chicago took a 2–0 lead.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] In the fifth inning, the White Sox continued to pile on the offense, as Happy Felsch singled off of Sallee, scoring Collins and Buck Weaver.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Sallee was then pulled out of the game, and Chicago had a 4–0 lead.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds broke the shutout in the sixth inning, when Heinie Groh hit a ground rule double, then came around to score on a single by Pat Duncan, cutting the White Sox lead to 4–1.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] That would be the only offense the Reds could muster, as Cicotte pitched a complete game victory, leading the White Sox to a 4–1 win and cutting the Reds series lead to 4–3.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] The eighth game of the series moved back to Comiskey Park in Chicago, as Hod Eller got the start for Cincinnati, against Lefty Williams of the White Sox, in front of 32,930 fans.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] After Morrie Rath led off the game with a pop out, the Reds Jake Daubert singled to center field.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Heinie Groh then singled to right field, moving Daubert to second base.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Edd Roush then doubled to right field, scoring Daubert and giving the Reds a 1–0 lead.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Pat Duncan followed up with a double of his own, scoring both Groh and Roush as Cincinnati took a 3–0 lead.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] The White Sox then took Williams out of the game, replacing him with Bill James.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds added another run when Bill Rariden singled home Duncan.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] In the second inning, Heinie Groh singled off of James, then was brought home after a double by Edd Roush, as Cincinnati took a 5–0 lead.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] The White Sox got on the board in the third inning, as Shoeless Joe Jackson hit a home run to right field, cutting the Reds lead to 5–1.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] In the fifth inning, the Reds Larry Kopf tripled off of Bill James, and was brought home after a Greasy Neale single, making it 6-1 Cincinnati.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds continued to pour on the offense in the sixth inning, when Hod Eller singled off of James, followed by a walk by Morrie Rath, knocking James out of the game.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] The White Sox brought in Roy Wilkinson to pitch, however, Jake Daubert reached first base after an error, loading the bases.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Edd Roush then singled, scoring Eller and Rath, followed by a single by Pat Duncan, scoring Roush, and giving the Reds a 9–1 lead.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] In the eighth inning, Edd Roush led off the inning after being hit by a pitch, then moved to second after a Pat Duncan sacrifice bunt.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Roush came around to score after a single by Bill Rariden, extending the Reds lead to 10–1.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] In the bottom of the eighth inning, the White Sox made a last attempt to comeback, as a double by Shoeless Joe Jackson scored Eddie Collins and Buck Weaver, cutting the Reds lead to 10–3.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Chick Gandil tripled to right field, scoring Jackson, making it 10–4.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Swede Risberg then hit it to Reds center fielder Edd Roush, who made an error, allowing Gandil to score, and cut the lead to 10-5 for the Reds.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] Cincinnati got out of the inning after a Ray Schalk groundout to stop the comeback.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-cincinnati-reds-season] In the ninth, the White Sox threatened to score, however, Hod Eller shut them down, as Cincinnati won the game 10–5, and won the World Series for the first time in club history.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] The **1919 World Series** was the championship series in Major League Baseball (MLB) for the 1919 season.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] The 16th edition of the World Series, it matched the American League (AL) champion Chicago White Sox against the National League (NL) champion Cincinnati Reds.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] Although most World Series have been of the best-of-seven format, the 1919 World Series was a best-of-nine series (along with 1903, 1920, and 1921).
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] The National Baseball Commission decided to try the best-of-nine format partly to increase popularity of the sport and partly to generate more revenue.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] The events of the 1919 World Series are often associated with the Black Sox Scandal, in which several members of the Chicago franchise conspired with gamblers, allegedly led by organized crime figure Arnold Rothstein, to throw the series.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] This led the various franchise owners to install Kenesaw Mountain Landis as the first Commissioner of Baseball in 1920.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] In August 1921, despite being acquitted from criminal charges, eight players from the White Sox were banned from organized baseball for either fixing the series or having knowledge about the fix without alerting the league.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] Dickey Kerr, another player on the team who was not involved in the scandal, was later suspended after holding out for more pay, but was eventually reinstated.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] They were the first players formally banned in the modern era, and, as it turned out, the template for how Landis would wield his authority throughout his tenure.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] On May 12, 2025, commissioner Rob Manfred lifted all permanent bans — including those of the Black Sox players — on the grounds that deceased players pose no threat to the integrity of the game.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] The nine players that were once banned by the MLB (most notably Shoeless Joe Jackson and Eddie Cicotte) are now considered eligible for entry into the Baseball Hall of Fame by as early as 2027.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] In 1919, the Chicago White Sox, who had won the World Series two years earlier, had the best record in the American League (AL).
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] Most of the same players had defeated the New York Giants in the 1917 series, four games to two.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] They had fallen to sixth place in the American League in 1918, largely as a result of losing their best player, Shoeless Joe Jackson, and a few other teammates to World War I service.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] The team's owner, Charles Comiskey, fired manager Pants Rowland after the season and replaced him with William "Kid" Gleason, who had played over twenty years in the majors but had never managed before.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] The 88–52 White Sox won the American League pennant again in 1919, by 3+1⁄2 games over the Cleveland Indians (world champions the following year).
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] Jackson was the unquestioned star of the White Sox.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] The left fielder hit .351 that season, fourth in the league and in the AL's top five in slugging percentage, RBI, total bases and base hits.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] He was not the only star in a lineup with hardly a weak spot, as former Philadelphia Athletics superstar leadoff hitter Eddie Collins, one of the greatest second basemen of all time, was still going strong in his early thirties, hitting .319 with a .400 on-base percentage.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] Right fielder Nemo Leibold hit .302 with 81 runs scored.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] First baseman Chick Gandil hit .290, third baseman Buck Weaver .296, and center fielder Oscar "Hap" Felsch hit .275 and tied Jackson for the team lead in home runs with only seven (as the dead-ball era was coming to a close).
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] Even typical "good field, no hit" catcher Ray Schalk hit .282 that year, and shortstop Swede Risberg was not an automatic out with the .256 average and 38 RBI.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] Gleason's bench contained two impressive hitters, outfielder Shano Collins and infielder Fred McMullin, both veterans of the 1917 series.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] Eddie Cicotte recorded a 29–7 record, leading the league in wins and ranking second in earned run average to Walter Johnson.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] Claude "Lefty" Williams finished with a 23–11 record and a 2.64 ERA.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] Dickey Kerr started 17 games and recorded a 13–7 record with a 2.88 ERA.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] Urban "Red" Faber had an 11–9 record with a 3.83 ERA in 20 starts.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] Faber was unable to pitch in the series due to illness, leaving manager Kid Gleason with three starting pitchers.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] However, all was not well in the White Sox camp.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] In contrast to the White Sox, the 1919 Cincinnati Reds were upstarts.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] They had finished no higher than third since 1900, and then only twice, before winning the National League (NL) pennant handily in 1919.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] The Reds' greatest star was center fielder Edd Roush, who led the league in hitting at .321 and, like the White Sox's Jackson, was in the top five of their respective leagues in most important hitting categories.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] Third baseman Heinie Groh was the other great hitter on the team at .310 with a .392 on-base percentage and 79 runs scored.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] Slick-fielding first baseman Jake Daubert, a two-time National League batting champion with Brooklyn earlier in the decade, also scored 79 runs and hit .276, while catcher Ivey Wingo hit .273.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] The rest of the team was unheralded, including second baseman Morrie Rath, a .264 hitter with no power but a good on-base percentage, and shortstop Larry Kopf, a .270 singles hitter.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] The corner outfielders were decidedly weaker hitters, with former Phillies star left fielder Sherry Magee's .215 in 56 games and right fielder Earle "Greasy" Neale's .242 with little power.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] This would prompt Moran to start rookie Pat Duncan in left field in the 1919 series.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] However, the Reds had a strong pitching rotation.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] The team's big three included Hod Eller (20–9, 2.39), Dutch Ruether (19–6, 1.82) and Slim Sallee (21–7, 2.06), all among the league leaders in various categories.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] They were backed by three other pitchers who were almost as successful: Jimmy Ring at only 10–9 but 2.26, Ray Fisher at 14–5 and 2.17 with five shutouts, and Cuban Dolf Luque at 10–3 and 2.63, former and future Giant who would win the last game of the 1933 World Series in long relief for New York.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] The conspiring players on the White Sox got an unexpected assist when a flu-stricken Faber was left off the World Series roster.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] Indeed, years later, catcher Schalk said that had Faber been healthy, there never would have been a fix (since he almost certainly would have gotten starts that went to Cicotte or Williams).
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] Despite their many wins on the field, the Sox were an unhappy team.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] Many observers blame their attitude on Comiskey's stinginess, despite the fact that the 1919 White Sox payroll was third highest in the AL, behind only Boston and New York.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] Stories about the scandal have usually included Comiskey in its gallery of subsidiary villains, focusing in particular on his intentions regarding a clause in Cicotte's contract that would have paid the knuckleballer an additional $10,000 bonus for winning thirty games.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] According to Eliot Asinof's account of the events, *Eight Men Out*, Cicotte was "rested" for the season's final two weeks after reaching his 29th win presumably to deny him the bonus, but the truth may be more complex.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] Cicotte won his 29th game on September 19, had an ineffective start on September 24 and was pulled after a few innings in a tuneup on the season's final day, September 28 (three days before the World Series opener).
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] In addition, Cicotte reportedly agreed to the fix the same day he won his 29th game before he could have known of any efforts to deny him a chance to win his 30th.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] The story was probably true with regard to the 1917 season, however, when Cicotte won 28 games and hurled the White Sox to the championship.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] The first game began at 3 pm at Cincinnati's Redland Field, with 30,511 fans in the stands and ticket scalpers outside the park raking in at least $50 per ticket.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] Chicago failed to score in the top of the first.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] In the bottom of the inning, Cicotte (who was paid his $10,000 the night before the series began) took the mound and hit the leadoff hitter (and former teammate), Morrie Rath, in the back with his second pitch, a prearranged signal to Arnold Rothstein that the fix was on.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] Even so, the game remained close for a while, due in part to some excellent defense from the conspirators, seeking to deflect suspicion from themselves.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] In the fourth, however, Cicotte "went haywire" (again according to Meany, *op. cit.*), allowing a number of hits in succession climaxed by a two-out triple to the opposing pitcher, as the Reds scored five times to break a 1–1 tie.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] Cicotte was relieved at that point, but the damage was done and the Reds went on to add three more runs in later innings and win 9–1.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] Sportswriters thought that a bad throw by Cicotte to Risberg in the fourth inning, which prevented a possible double play, was suspicious.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] By that evening, there already were signs that things were going wrong.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] Only Cicotte, who had shrewdly demanded his $10,000 in advance, had been paid.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] "Sleepy" Bill Burns and Maharg met with Abe Attell, the former world boxing champ and Rothstein's intermediary, but he withheld the next installment ($20,000) nonetheless to bet on the next game.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] The next morning Gandil met Attell and again demanded money, but again to no avail.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] Although they had not received their money, the players were still willing to go through with the fix.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] "Lefty" Williams, the starting pitcher in Game 2, was not going to be as obvious as Cicotte.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] After a shaky start, he pitched well until the fourth inning, when he walked three and gave up as many runs.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] After that he became virtually unhittable again, giving up only one more run; but lack of clutch hitting, with Gandil a particularly guilty party, led to a 4–2 White Sox loss.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] Attell was still in no mood to pay up afterwards, but Burns managed to get hold of $10,000 and gave it to Gandil, who distributed it among the conspirators.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] The teams headed northwest to Comiskey Park in Chicago for Game 3 the next day, with no days off for travel in this Series.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] Rookie pitcher Dickey Kerr, the Game 3 starter for the Sox, was not in on the fix.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] The original plan was for the conspirators, who disliked Kerr, to lose this game, but by now dissent among the players meant that the plan was in disarray.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] Burns still had faith and gathered the last of his resources to bet on Cincinnati.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] It was a decision that would leave him broke, as Chicago scored early—with Gandil himself driving in two runs—and Kerr was masterful, holding the Reds to three hits in a 3–0 complete game shutout.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] Cicotte took the mound again for Game 4, and was determined not to look as bad as he had in Game 1.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] For the first four innings, he and Reds pitcher Jimmy Ring matched zeroes.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] With one out in the fifth, Cicotte fielded a slow roller by Pat Duncan but threw wildly to first for a two-base error.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] The next man up, Larry Kopf, singled to left; Cicotte cut off the throw from Jackson and fumbled the ball, allowing Duncan to score.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] The home crowd was stunned by the veteran pitcher's obvious mistake.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] Cicotte then surrendered a double to Greasy Neale which scored Kopf to make it 2–0; this was enough of a lead for Ring, who hurled a three-hit shutout of his own, matching Kerr's in Game 3.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] After the game "Sport" Sullivan came through with $20,000 for the players, which Gandil split equally among Risberg, Felsch, and Williams, who was due to start Game 5 the next day.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] Both starters, Williams and Cincinnati's Hod Eller, pitched excellently at first, with neither allowing a runner past first until the top of the sixth, when Eller himself hit a blooper that fell between Felsch and Jackson.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] Felsch's throw was offline, sending Eller all the way to third.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] Leadoff hitter Morrie Rath then singled over the drawn-in infield, scoring Eller.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] Heinie Groh walked before Edd Roush's double—the result of more doubtful defense from Felsch—brought home two more runs, with Roush scoring shortly thereafter.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] Eller pitched well enough (he struck out nine batters, including a then-World Series record six in a row, since tied by Moe Drabowsky in the 1966 World Series opener) for the four runs to stand up, and the Reds were only one game away from their first world championship.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] The Series reverted to Cincinnati for Game 6.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] Dickey Kerr, starting for the White Sox, was less dominant than in Game 3.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] Aided by three White Sox errors, the Reds jumped out to a 4–0 lead before Chicago fought back, tying the game at 4–4 in the sixth, which remained the score into extra innings.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] In the top of the tenth, Gandil drove in Weaver to make it 5–4, and Kerr closed it out to record his — and Chicago's — second win.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] Despite the rumors already circulating about Cicotte's erratic performances in Games 1 and 4, White Sox manager Kid Gleason showed faith in his ace for Game 7.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] This time, the knuckleballer did not let him down.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] Chicago scored early and, for once, it was Cincinnati that committed errors.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] The Reds threatened only briefly in the sixth before losing 4–1, and suddenly the Series was relatively close again.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] This marked the only time in World Series history that the winner of Game 7 did not ultimately go on to win the series.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] This did not go unnoticed by Sullivan and Rothstein, who were suddenly worried.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] Before the Series started, the Sox had been strong favorites and few doubted they could win two games in a row—presuming that they were *trying* to win.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] Rothstein had been too smart to bet on individual games, but had $270,000 riding on Cincinnati to win the Series.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] The night before Game 8, Williams—the scheduled starter—was supposedly visited by an associate of Sullivan's known as Harry F.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] He left no doubt that if Williams failed to blow the game in the first inning, he and his wife would be in serious danger.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] Chicago wouldn't see another Game 7 for over a century.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] Whatever Williams had been told made its impression.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] In the first, throwing nothing but mediocre fastballs, he gave up four straight one-out hits for three runs before Gleason relieved him with "Big" Bill James, who allowed one of Williams' baserunners to score.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] James continued ineffective and, although the Sox rallied in the eighth, the Reds came away with a 10–5 victory for a five-games-to-three Series win.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] Jackson hit the only homer of the Series in the third inning after the Reds had built a 5–0 lead.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] Immediately after the Series ended, rumors were rife from coast to coast that the games had been thrown.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] Journalist Hugh Fullerton of the *Chicago Herald and Examiner*, disgusted by the display of ineptitude with which the White Sox had "thrown" the series, wrote that no World Series should ever be played again.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] Jackson led all players with his .375 average.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] Some believed that most of his offensive potency came in games that were not fixed and/or when the game seemed out of reach.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] He hit the Series' lone home run in the eighth and final game, a solo shot in the third inning, by which time the Reds were already ahead 5–0.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] His five hits with runners in scoring position came in: Game 6, sixth inning with Kerr pitching; Game 7, first and third innings; Game 8, two in the four-run eighth.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] Shoeless Joe had 12 hits overall, a World Series record at that time and tied for the most in an eight-game series.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] The Reds would make their next World Series appearance two decades later, but were swept by the New York Yankees, becoming the last victim of a Yankees dynasty of four straight championships from 1936 to 1939.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] They would win their next championship in 1940 over the Detroit Tigers in seven games after being nine outs away from elimination in Game 7.
[src:buck-weaver/1919-world-series] The scandal cast a shadow that lasted decades.
[src:buck-weaver/1920-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1920 throughout the world.
[src:buck-weaver/1920-in-baseball] All Negro leagues standings below are per MLB and Seamheads.
[src:buck-weaver/1920-in-baseball] This was the first season of organized Negro league baseball.
[src:buck-weaver/1920-in-baseball] The first Negro National League would run for the next decade and is considered to be of major league status.
[src:buck-weaver/1920-in-baseball] The Chicago American Giants, managed by league founder and former player Rube Foster, won the first league pennant.
[src:buck-weaver/1920-in-baseball] A loose confederation of teams were gathered in the East to compete with the West, however East teams did not organize a formal league as the West did.
[src:buck-weaver/buck-weaver] Weaver was born in Pottstown, Pennsylvania, to Daniel Weaver and Susan Snell and began his major league career on April 11, 1912, as a shortstop for the White Sox.
[src:buck-weaver/buck-weaver] Weaver switched to third base in 1917 after Swede Risberg joined the team.
[src:buck-weaver/buck-weaver] An excellent fielder, Weaver was known as the only third baseman in the league against whom Ty Cobb would not bunt.
[src:buck-weaver/buck-weaver] He led the majors in sacrifice hits in 1915 and 1916.
[src:buck-weaver/buck-weaver] In the famous 1919 World Series, Weaver batted .324, tallying 11 hits.
[src:buck-weaver/buck-weaver] After the Series was over, many suspicious reporters made allusions to a possible fix.
[src:buck-weaver/buck-weaver] However some sportswriters praised Weaver for his efforts all along during the World Series.
[src:buck-weaver/buck-weaver] Despite this, Weaver was banned by Commissioner Kenesaw Mountain Landis for having knowledge of the fix and failing to tell team officials.
[src:buck-weaver/buck-weaver] Weaver successfully sued White Sox owner Charles Comiskey for his 1921 salary.
[src:buck-weaver/buck-weaver] When Shoeless Joe Jackson did the same, the jury voted 11–1 in favor of Jackson.
[src:buck-weaver/buck-weaver] However, the judge set aside the jury verdict after Comiskey produced Jackson's grand jury testimony about the fix.
[src:buck-weaver/buck-weaver] Despite this success, however, Comiskey made no attempt to offer the confessions as evidence to obtain a similar ruling against Weaver.
[src:buck-weaver/buck-weaver] For the rest of his life, Weaver applied at least six times for reinstatement to baseball.
[src:buck-weaver/buck-weaver] The first time was on January 13, 1922, when Weaver unsuccessfully applied for reinstatement, which was rejected by Landis.
[src:buck-weaver/buck-weaver] One notable attempt to get reinstated came in 1927 in the wake of Tris Speaker/Ty Cobb betting scandal.
[src:buck-weaver/buck-weaver] Once again, Landis rejected it, with Landis telling a group of Weaver supporters that his presence at the meetings with the gamblers was sufficient to bar him.
[src:buck-weaver/buck-weaver] After this attempt failed, Weaver returned to Chicago and decided to play in the minor leagues again.
[src:buck-weaver/buck-weaver] Later in life, Weaver contacted a New York City attorney who vowed to get him reinstated.
[src:buck-weaver/buck-weaver] Weaver sent his legal papers and correspondence to New York; however, they were never returned.
[src:buck-weaver/buck-weaver] To this day, baseball historians have been unable to find Weaver's legal files.
[src:buck-weaver/buck-weaver] In 1953, Weaver applied for reinstatement one last time to Commissioner Ford Frick, which was ignored.
[src:buck-weaver/buck-weaver] The letter Weaver wrote to Frick is prominently displayed in Cooperstown’s Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum.
[src:buck-weaver/buck-weaver] Weaver died from a heart attack on January 31, 1956, at the age of 65.
[src:buck-weaver/buck-weaver] On May 13, 2025, Commissioner Rob Manfred reinstated Weaver and other deceased players from the ineligible list, including Pete Rose and Shoeless Joe Jackson.
[src:buck-weaver/buck-weaver] Many parts of the story portrayed in the 1988 movie *Eight Men Out* are told from Buck Weaver's point of view, with Weaver being played by John Cusack.
[src:buck-weaver/buck-weaver] Harry Stein also used Weaver as a co-narrator in his critically acclaimed Black Sox novel *Hoopla* (1983), where Stein's Weaver reiterates that his loyalty to his teammates compelled him not to inform baseball authorities about the Series fix.
[src:buck-weaver/buck-weaver] With the 2005 World Series set to begin and the White Sox about to capture their first championship since 1917, *Chicago Tribune* columnist Mike Downey implored Commissioner Bud Selig to rescind Weaver's ban.
[src:buck-weaver/buck-weaver] His column of October 20, 2005, cited catcher Ray Schalk's condemnation of "the seven" Sox in on the fix, not eight.
[src:buck-weaver/buck-weaver] Weaver's niece, Pat Anderson, told Downey: "You can't understand why someone else would be so obtuse.
[src:buck-weaver/buck-weaver] (Cook) Follett, attended the 2003 All-Star Game, held that year by the White Sox at U.S.
[src:buck-weaver/buck-weaver] Cellular Field, to personally appeal to Commissioner Bud Selig for her uncle's reinstatement.
[src:buck-weaver/buck-weaver] The *Tribune* reported a quote from Weaver: "There are murderers who serve a sentence and then get out.
